Add dedicated Bamboo Spec builder for the MSBuild task. Here is how it is modeled using the AnyTask:
{code:java}
private AnyTask addMSBuildTask() {
Map<String, String> configuration = new MapBuilder<String, String>()
.put("options", "/p:Configuration=Release")
.put("label", "MSBuild v14.0 (64bit)")
.put("solution", "MySolution.sln")
.put("environmentVariables", "")
.put("workingSubDirectory", "")
.build();
AnyTask anyTask = new AnyTask(new AtlassianModule("com.atlassian.bamboo.plugin.dotnet:msbuild"))
.description("Build")
.configuration(configuration);
return anyTask;
}{code}

When configuring a perforce repository type (following the steps for SVN, Mercurial, and CVS: https://docs.atlassian.com/bamboo-specs-docs/latest/#svn], Bamboo complains:
{noformat}
com.atlassian.bamboo.specs.api.exceptions.PropertiesValidationException: Plan branch / workflow: Default plan repository doesn't support 'BRANCH' workflow. Don't use this setting or choose another repository as default{noformat}
even if the branch management is configured to manual (which should be the default by the way).

{panel}
h3. Problem

New plan branch is automatically deleted due to last commit date from the newly created branch. UI is not clear about the strategy Bamboo will use to expire the plan branch. The branch is new but its last commit is old.
h3. Steps to reproduce:
 # Make sure Bamboo is configured with application links to Bitbucket server
# Make sure Admin REST API is enabled with system property {{-Datlassian.darkfeature.bamboo.experimental.rest.admin.enabled=true}}
 # Create a plan with a repository that has old commits
 # Configure the branch management to create the plan branch automatically. Make sure the "Delete plan branches after a period of inactivity" is set for 7 days
 # Navigate to your repository and create a checkout an old revision (let's say 2 weeks old - need to be older than a 7 days)
{noformat}
git checkout eeb81d64e94f44f399212d5d4fc2eb5f0622208f
{noformat}

 # Create a new branch from it
{noformat}
git checkout -b newbranch
git push origin newbranch
{noformat}

 # Wait until the plan branch is created in Bamboo (usually 5min with application links configured)
 # Run the branch expiry job
{code:java}
curl -u <admin_user> -p -H "Content-Type: application/json" -X POST -d '{"name":"branchExpiryJob", "groupName":"branchExpiryGroup"}' 'http://localhost:8085/rest/admin/latest/scheduler/jobs/trigger'
{code}

h3. Expected results:

The branch was just created and from the UI perspective it is fairly new and should not be expired before the 7 days of inactivity
h3. Actual results:

The plan branch *newbranch* is expired
h3. Suggestions for resolution:
 # Store the branch creation date (instead of last commit date) if this information is available and use this new date until a commit newer than this date is added to the branch *OR*
 # Update the UI in such a way that the expiry strategy (considering commit date) is more clear to end users{panel}

Same as build plans, deployment plans creation using Specs API would be a great feature. This feature is nowhere mentioned except in Bamboo Specs Reference:
{quote}Bamboo Specs do not support deployment plans at the moment.{quote}
I cannot find any information of when is this function going to be implemented or if it is even in plans for development.

h3. Problem Definition
After we submit a plan to Bamboo using Bamboo Specs, after we delete it from the Bamboo UI there is a small delay while Bamboo completes background deletion tasks. If the plan is resubmitted via Specs it fails with unhelpful error message (even with DEBUG enabled):
{code}
2017-05-19 15:43:58,061 INFO [BambooServer] Publishing plan PRJ-PLANKEY4
2017-05-19 15:43:58,480 INFO [BambooServer] An error occurred while publishing plan PRJ-PLANKEY4: No value present
2017-05-19 15:43:58,481 DEBUG [BambooServer] {"message":"No value present","status-code":500}
{code}

h3. Suggested Solution
Provide an error message that informs the user why the plan was rejected.
